<section class="card">
  <h2>About Radishes</h2>

  <p class="tagline">
    Ultra-fast cool-season crop—built for tight frost windows.
  </p>

  <p class="lede">
    <strong>Radishes mature quickly and tolerate light frost.</strong>
    For GrowByDate modeling, frost is defined as 32°F (0°C). In a typical year (1991–2020 climate normals at the 50% probability level), radishes are rarely limited by first frost. Instead, they are limited by heat and growth speed.
  </p>

  <p>
    In short seasons, radishes are one of the most reliable crops because they require minimal time and modest heat accumulation. They are often used to test early spring soil readiness.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Quick Planning Reference</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Direct sow:</strong> 4 weeks before to 4 weeks after last frost</li>
    <li><strong>Days to maturity:</strong> 20–35 days (variety-dependent)</li>
    <li><strong>Frost tolerance:</strong> Light to moderate (brief dips near 32°F / 0°C tolerated)</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="fine muted">
    These are baseline ranges. Heat spikes often reduce quality more than frost.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Temperature Profile</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Optimal growth:</strong> 50–70°F (10–21°C)</li>
    <li><strong>Slow growth:</strong> Below ~40°F (4°C)</li>
    <li><strong>Heat stress:</strong> Above ~80°F (27°C) causes pithiness</li>
    <li><strong>Planning frost boundary:</strong> 32°F (0°C)</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Radishes tolerate light frost, but repeated hard freezes can damage foliage.
    In most climates, quality declines from heat before frost becomes limiting.
  </p>

  <p class="fine">
    For frost definitions and freeze types, see:
    <a href="/guides/light-freeze-vs-hard-freeze/">Light freeze vs hard freeze</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Spring & Fall Timing</h2>

  <p>
    Radishes fit easily into both spring and fall planting windows:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Spring crop:</strong> Sow early into workable soil for quick harvest before heat.</li>
    <li><strong>Fall crop:</strong> Count backward from first frost and allow minimal buffer (maturity is fast).</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Use the <a href="/tools/first-frost-planner/">First Frost Planner</a> to anchor fall sowing dates.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Typical GDD Requirement</h2>

  <p><strong>Base temperature:</strong> 50°F (10°C)</p>
  <p><strong>Approximate GDD needed:</strong> ~300–500 GDD (base 50)</p>

  <p>
    Radishes have a very modest heat requirement. Even in cool springs, they usually accumulate enough GDD to mature within a short window.
  </p>

  <p class="fine muted" style="margin-top:14px;">
    GDD = ((Daily High + Daily Low) ÷ 2) − 50
  </p>

  <div class="actions">
    <a class="button subtle" href="/tools/growing-degree-day-planner/">Use the GDD Planner</a>
  </div>

  <p class="fine">
    For the combined frost + heat framework, see:
    <a href="/guides/how-frost-dates-and-growing-degree-days-work-together/">How frost dates and Growing Degree Days work together</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Minimum Frost-Free Days</h2>

  <p>
    Most radish varieties mature in just <strong>20–35 frost-free days</strong>.
    Because they tolerate light frost, effective harvest windows often extend slightly beyond first frost in mild falls.
  </p>

  <div class="actions">
    <a class="button subtle" href="/tools/frost-date-finder/">Check Your Frost-Free Season</a>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Short-Season Viability Flag</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Good choice under 100 days?</strong> Yes (extremely reliable)</li>
    <li><strong>Risky under 90 days?</strong> Rarely; short maturity minimizes risk</li>
    <li><strong>Needs season extension?</strong> Usually no</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>First Frost Sensitivity</h2>

  <p>
    Radishes tolerate brief light frost near 32°F (0°C), but sustained hard freezes can damage foliage and halt growth.
    For planning consistency, treat 32°F (0°C) as the boundary date.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Early-Maturing Strategy</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Sow as soon as soil is workable in spring</li>
    <li>Use succession sowing for continuous harvest</li>
    <li>In fall, allow slight buffer beyond labeled days-to-maturity</li>
    <li>Prioritize cool-season windows to preserve quality</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Planning Model</h2>

  <p class="muted">
    Frost → Season Length → GDD → Crop Requirement → Risk Margin
  </p>

  <p>
    In a typical year, radishes are viable in nearly all short-season climates because of their rapid maturity and modest heat demand.
    The primary constraint is avoiding heat stress rather than frost.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <h3>Can radishes survive frost?</h3>
  <p>
    Yes. Light frost near 32°F (0°C) is usually tolerated, though repeated hard freezes can cause damage.
  </p>

  <h3>Why are my radishes woody?</h3>
  <p>
    Heat stress or delayed harvest commonly causes pithiness and woody texture.
  </p>

  <h3>Are radishes good for very short seasons?</h3>
  <p>
    Yes. Their 20–35 day maturity makes them one of the safest crops in tight frost windows.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Summary</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Use 32°F (0°C) as the frost boundary (50% probability, 1991–2020 normals).</li>
    <li>Radishes mature quickly and tolerate light frost.</li>
    <li>Typical requirement: 20–35 days, ~300–500 GDD (base 50).</li>
    <li>Model viability using frost window + seasonal heat budget + variety requirement + risk margin.</li>
  </ul>
</section>